comments.quote:
The joint distribution in (1) is mathematically expressed as
\begin{equation}
p_{\theta}(\mathbf{A}, \mathbf{C}, \mathbf{Z}) = \prod_{i=1}^{N} p_{\theta}(\mathbf{z}_i) p_{\theta}(c_i | \mathbf{z}_i) \prod_{(i,j) \in E} p_{\theta}(a_{ij} | c_i, c_j, \mathbf{z}_i, \mathbf{z}_j)
\end{equation}

where $D_{KL} ( .||. )$ represents the KL-divergence between two distributions. The distribution $q_{\phi} ( \mathbf{z}_i, \mathbf{z}_j, c_i, c_j|I )$ in the third term of Eq. (7) is factorized into two conditionally independent distributions i.e.
\begin{equation}
q_{\phi} ( \mathbf{z}_i, \mathbf{z}_j, c_i, c_j|I ) = q_{\phi} ( \mathbf{z}_i, c_i | I ) q_{\phi} ( \mathbf{z}_j, c_j | I )
\end{equation}

Finally, a softmax is applied as follows
\begin{equation}
q_{\phi} ( c_i = k | \mathbf{z}_i, I ) = \text{softmax}_k \left( \alpha (\mathbf{z}_i^T \mathbf{g}_k) + \frac{(1-\alpha)}{|N_i|} \sum_{j \in N_i} (\mathbf{z}_j^T \mathbf{g}_k) \right)
\end{equation}
